(62, 1, '2019-03-13 13:54:03', '2019-03-13 13:54:03', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>10 Million word contemporary Sinhala text corpus for language research</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UCSC mini corpus contains 10 million Sinhala words collected from Sinhala newspaper articles. There are around 135,000 distinct words in the corpus and it comprises 2794 text files containing editorials, feature articles, foreign news and sports news.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>100K word English, Sinhala parallel corpus</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>English-Sinhala parallel corpus is for language researchers who are involved in English-Sinhala machine translation. The corpus contains 4,301 English sentences along with corresponding Sinhala translations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>500k Sinhala tagged corpus</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UCSC tagged corpus contains 500K words, manually tagged by Sinhala linguists using UCSC Sinhala POS tagset (version 1). Words that do not belong to any defined tag are tagged with a question mark (?)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>1300 word Sinhala WordNet for language technology improvement</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UCSC Sinhala wordnet (version 1) contains 1,075 word senses and each sense includes synsets along with the corresponding English word, Princeton ID for the synset, POS Category and the Gloss.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>UCSC Sinhala POS tagset</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A Part of Speech Tagset for Sinhala (version 1). There are 28 different word class tags not including the punctuation marks. A punctuation mark itself is considered as a separate tag for that particular mark.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>List of proper names for language research</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A list of Sinhala proper names including country names, Sinhala personal names, names of Sri Lankan and international cities, names of Sinhala artists, Sri Lankan rivers and reservoirs. Currently there are around 20,800 proper name entries.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>NamedEntity Tagged Corpus</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sinhala Named Entity Tagged Corpus consists around 83K words that have been tagged for person names, location names and organization names as Named Entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>List of Sinhala Functional Words</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A list of 425 Sinhala functional words with Sinhala conjunctions, determinants, interjections, particles and post positions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Sinhala_NE_Data (including person and place name entities)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Ingiya English-Sinhala dictionary database</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The English-Sinhala dictionary database used in the ingiya English-Sinhala dictionary add-on. This database consists of ≈36,000 English word entries and the corresponding Sinhala meanings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>400K Distinct word list</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A list of 400K distinct words extracted from the UCSC Sinhala text corpus.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Speech corpora for Sinhala speech processing</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Female voice corpus</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Speech corpus with 3000 Sinhala utterances spoken by a single female speaker. This corpus was initially designed to built an Automatic Speech Recognition System (ASR) for Sinhala. Spoken utterances were selected considering the most frequently used words in Sinhala.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Male voice corpus</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Speech corpus with 625 Sinhala utterances spoken by a single male speaker. This corpus was initially designed to built a Text to Speech Syatem (TTS) for Sinhala.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>2000 voice corpus</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Speech corpus with 74,000 Sinhala utterances spoken by various speakers representing both male and female in different age groups. This corpus was initially designed to built a song request application for mobile phones.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Sinhala NEWS Corpus</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A speech corpus with 8000 utterances of recorded Sinhala NEWS from both male and female announcers. This is still an ongoing project.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Lexical Resources', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'lexical-resources', '', '', '2019-03-13 13:54:06', '2019-03-13 13:54:06', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/ucsc4/wordpress503/?page_id=62', 0, 'page', '', 0),
